BHP Billiton: Turbulence Ahead - BHP Billiton plc (NYSE:BBL) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»BHP Billiton: Turbulence AheadMar. 7.17 | About: BHP Billiton (BBL) Christiaan Casper Growth at reasonable price, long only, value, long-term horizonSummaryCommodity prices have been on the recovery which leads to tailwinds in the mining sector.
        BHP Billiton faces significant short term firm-specific risks.
        Investors may want to hold off investing until the strike ends and economics consequences concerning the tailings dam failure are known.
        Investment Thesis BHP Billiton (NYSE:BBL) operates in a challenging environment and is subject to multiple risk factors. Although commodity prices have made a significant comeback over the past months, the risk factors may hint at an economic, mostly firm-specific, setback. I argue that until there is more certainty with regard to litigation costs, investors may want to postpone their investment decision. Introduction BHP Billiton is a producer of natural resources including iron ore, metallurgical coal, nickel and copper, as well as crude oil and gas in Australia and the Americas. The company has come into existence after a merger between an Australian (NYSE:BHP) and British (Billiton) mining company in 2001. The products are sold worldwide. The annual report ranges from July 1st till June 30th. Considering commodity prices (and profit margins) recovering and the price of iron ore having increased just short of 90% over the past 12 months, is investing in BHP Billiton a wise decision? 

 Source: Business Insider Essentials and dividends BHP Billiton has a return on equity of 4.39%. By comparison metal mining average return on equity was 3.94% according to csimarket.com. The company trades at a price-to-book ratio of 1.59 and has a strong operating margin of 21.82%, a PE ratio of 36.49 and EPS of 0.93. BHP Billiton has a long term debt of little over 30 billion dollars. On the other hand it is apparent that BHP Billiton is able to bear its interest expense as it has a current ratio of 1.79 which is significantly above 1. The currency risk (which will be more thoroughly discussed later) it is exposed to will likely not affect the currency ratio to the point that the company will not be able to pay its short term liabilities. A quick ratio of 1.50 is a healthy sign as well.  

 Source: Company Data
 BHP Billiton has introduced a new dividend policy in 2016 and intends to payout a minimum of 50% of underlying attributable profit at every reporting period: The dividend policy provides for a minimum 50 percent payout of Underlying attributable profit at every reporting period. For FY2016, the Board determined a final dividend of 14 US cents per share, which is covered by free cash flow. This dividend comprises the minimum payout per share plus an additional amount of six US cents per share. At every reporting period, the Board will assess the Company's capacity to pay amounts additional to the minimum payment, in accordance with the capital allocation framework. The resulting dividend may actually turn out to be greater than the minimum as illustrated by the additional 6 cents per share (75%) to the minimum payout of 8 cents in this case. The trailing twelve month dividend rate is set at 0.56 cents while the 4 year average dividend yield is 4.16%. 

 Source: Seeking Alpha BHP Billiton will go ex-dividend on March 8th, 2017, for the New York and Johannesburg stock exchanges and will go ex-dividend on March 9th for the Australian and London stock exchanges. The record date which is also the currency conversion rate will be March 10th, 2017. The payment will take place on March 28th, 2017. The dividend prospect is as follows: 

 Source: Company Data Rising prices for commodities relate to stronger profitability. An update from the operational report of January 25th, 2017 shows indicates the following prices changes with most notably an increase of 116% in hard coking coal. 

 Source: Company Data
 Risks Compared to 2015 BHP Billiton's 2016 product prices have considerably declined. The result is that tight margins have affected the firm as it is its policy is to sell products at prevailing market prices. The recovering prices should positively affect future earnings and divers products may hedge some of the price risk. However the annual report illustrates: The diversity provided by our broad portfolio of commodities does not necessarily insulate the Company from the effects of price changes. Note from the table below that all average prices from 2016 have declined compared to 2015. This proves that mining product diversification is no reliable hedge against price risk. 

 Source: Company Data BHP Billiton is subject to currency risk as the majority of its cash and cash equivalents are measured in US dollars. Varying exchange rates may adversely affect BHP Billiton in the future. On the other hand its interest bearing liabilities also contain a large share of Euros and Pounds and on top of that, the company's operations occur in a large variety of currencies, which are all subject to risk from fluctuating exchange rates. BHP Billiton states: The Australian dollar, Chilean peso and US dollar are some of the currencies influencing our operating costs. We do not generally believe active currency hedging provides long-term benefits to our shareholders." As a result currency hedging is only undergone under exceptional circumstances and short term results are subject to currency risk. An immediate threat is posed by the strike at the company's mine in Chile. As of March 10th, BHP Billiton may approach workers individually to end the strike but until that time, no production is going on. The strike will affect results for the current quarter.
 Lastly, there is a significant litigation risk which should be accounted for. On November 5th, 2015, the Samarco dam experienced a tailings dam failure which flooded lower areas, killing 19 people and sending mining waste downstream. As a result BHP Billiton (among others) is now defendant concerning a claim of approximately 47 billion US dollars. The operational review states: On 18 January 2017, Samarco, Vale and BHP Billiton Brasil have also entered into a preliminary agreement with the Federal Prosecutors' Office in Brazil in relation to the Fundão tailings dam failure on 5 November 2015(3) (Preliminary Agreement). The Preliminary Agreement outlines the process and timeline for negotiation of a settlement of the BRL 155 billion (approximately US$47.5 billion) Civil Claim relating to the dam failure. The result is that BHP Billiton will likely incur significant costs in the near future regarding litigation. Given the broad range of risks BHP Billiton faces an investment in the company is subject to a large number of uncertainties. Low commodity prices, currency risk and litigation are some of the risks which should be accounted for. There are numerous other risk factors which should be accounted for such as a general decrease in demand and possible governmental regulatory actions. It is noteworthy that BHP Billiton recognizes these risks and has transparently mentioned them in the annual report. However, to put the risks into perspective it is important to consider a future outlook of the company. Future outlook As of now it is uncertain when the litigious setback will occur. What is certain however, is that the benefits from the increased commodity prices will be incurred in the following fiscal quarters. The stock price, on the other hand already seems to have reacted to the increase in commodity prices with a rally over the past months.  

 Source: Seeking Alpha
 Results from the December 2016 half year will be promising due to asset divesting and a reimbursement. These results are not sustainable but will generate a one-off benefit. BHP Billiton expects Underlying attributable profit(1) in the December 2016 half year to include gains related to asset divestments in a range of approximately US$150 million to US$200 million (Underlying EBITDA(1) impact of US$175 million to US$225 million). In addition, the Group expects to record an exceptional item of US$164 million (US$115 million post-tax) related to the cancellation of the Caroona exploration license and subsequent reimbursement received during the December 2016 half year. In its operational review of January 25th, 2015, BHP Billiton has included an indication of the production for the coming quarters. The indication is positive as the company is planning on increasing its production in all sectors. However, if competitors implement the same strategy, overproduction may adversely affect prices. 

 Source: Company Data On a positive note, BHP Billiton gas incurred lower exploration costs in the copper sector: We have secured growth opportunities via brownfield exploration around our portfolio of existing assets, principally aimed at delineating and categorizing mineral deposits in resource basins near our existing operations, while advancing projects through the development pipeline, primarily in copper. This has enabled us to reduce brownfield exploration expenditure and to rationalize our Greenfield exploration program. As a result the exploration costs with regard to copper have greatly decreased in 2016 as seen in the comparative decrease of brownfield exploration costs.  

 Source: Company Data
 Conclusion It is uncertain whether commodity prices will continue to rise in the future and if margins and efficiency will increase. It seems that the stock price has already reacted to the increase in commodity prices but may be subject to a negative shock due to litigious consequences when they are incurred. In the short term BHP Billiton will likely benefit from one-off divesting income and reimbursement but also face significant risk factors. Investors may want to hold off investing until after the strike ends and litigation concerning the tailings dam is settled. On the other hand if prices continue to rise in the future, BHP Billiton faces a bright future.
Disclosure: I/we have no positions in any stocks mentioned, but may initiate a long position in BBL over the next 72 hours. 
